Don’t explain IoC and DI like textbook definitions. Experienced-level interviews expect you to explain:

Why Spring uses them
What problem they solve
How container lifecycle works
Real project usage
Difference between IoC and DI
Constructor injection vs field injection
Bean management

Most candidates fail because they only say:

“IoC means control transferred to Spring.”
“DI means injecting dependencies.”

That sounds junior.

Explain it like this instead:

IoC (Inversion of Control)
Interview Explanation

In traditional Java applications, objects create their dependencies manually using new keyword.
In Spring Boot, object creation and lifecycle management are handled by the Spring IoC Container.
This is called Inversion of Control because control of object creation moves from developer code to the Spring framework.

Traditional Java Without IoC
public class OrderService {

    private PaymentService paymentService = new PaymentService();

}

Problem:

Tight coupling
Hard to test
Hard to replace implementation
Difficult in microservices-scale projects

If tomorrow payment changes:

StripePaymentService
RazorpayPaymentService
PaypalPaymentService

you must modify code everywhere.

That becomes messy in large systems.

With Spring IoC
@Service
public class PaymentService {

}
@Service
public class OrderService {

    private final PaymentService paymentService;

    public OrderService(PaymentService paymentService) {
        this.paymentService = paymentService;
    }
}

Now:

Spring creates objects
Spring manages lifecycle
Spring injects dependency automatically
Classes become loosely coupled
Simple One-Line Experienced Explanation

IoC means Spring container takes responsibility for creating, managing, and controlling application objects instead of developers manually creating them.

DI (Dependency Injection)
Interview Explanation

Dependency Injection is the mechanism used to provide required objects (dependencies) into another object instead of the object creating them itself.

Real Meaning

OrderService depends on PaymentService.

Instead of:

new PaymentService()

Spring injects it.

That injection is DI.

Types of Dependency Injection
1. Constructor Injection (Preferred)
@Service
public class OrderService {

    private final PaymentService paymentService;

    public OrderService(PaymentService paymentService) {
        this.paymentService = paymentService;
    }
}

Why preferred:

Mandatory dependencies enforced
Easier unit testing
Immutable dependencies
Recommended by Spring

Say this in interview.

2. Setter Injection
@Autowired
public void setPaymentService(PaymentService paymentService) {
    this.paymentService = paymentService;
}

Used when dependency is optional.

3. Field Injection (Avoid Mostly)
@Autowired
private PaymentService paymentService;

Looks simple but:

Hard to test
Reflection-based
Not immutable
Hidden dependencies

Experienced interviewers like when you criticize field injection.

Difference Between IoC and DI

This is where many candidates fail.

Best Answer

IoC is the overall principle where control of objects is given to Spring container.
DI is the design pattern Spring uses to implement IoC by injecting dependencies into classes.

Real Project Flow Explanation

This sounds experienced:

During application startup, Spring scans classes annotated with @Component, @Service, @Repository, and @Controller.
It creates beans inside the IoC container.
When a class requires another dependency, Spring resolves and injects the bean automatically using DI.

Explain Bean Also

Interviewers often continue here.

Say:

Bean is an object managed by Spring IoC container.

Example:

@Service
public class PaymentService {
}

PaymentService becomes a Spring Bean.

Advanced Point (Experienced-Level)

Add this:

Because of IoC and DI, applications become loosely coupled, maintainable, testable, and scalable, which is very important in microservices architecture.

Strong Interview Flow (Memorize This)

In Spring Boot, IoC means object creation and lifecycle management are handled by Spring container instead of manually creating objects using new.
DI is the mechanism where Spring injects required dependencies into classes.
This reduces tight coupling and improves maintainability and testability.
Usually I prefer constructor injection because it supports immutability and easier unit testing.

That sounds like someone who actually worked in projects, not someone memorizing definitions.
